[2026-03-11T00:27:32Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01BzzxMan5dS9n2Gt7iP1Br9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WMRLjmV5CzLpKMdGs7Wzcq","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":596,"cache_read_input_tokens":54108,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":596,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Dpfoc28ynQqDwHgSbSci6o","session_id":"2f8bcbbf-b8aa-4f20-9779-dee3a5fa668b","uuid":"4639ed72-bda5-461b-af2c-d5bf1ae260eb"}
[2026-03-11T00:27:32Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WMRLjmV5CzLpKMdGs7Wzcq","type":"tool_result","content":"     1Ôćĺ# Workflows\n     2Ôćĺ\n     3ÔćĺCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4Ôćĺ\n     5Ôćĺ## Workflow Locations\n     6Ôćĺ\n     7ÔćĺCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8Ôćĺ\n     9Ôćĺ**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) ÔÇö Run inside a Docker\n    10Ôćĺcontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11Ôćĺstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12Ôćĺ\n    13Ôćĺ**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) ÔÇö Runs on the host machine as the daemon\n    14Ôćĺprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15Ôćĺdispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16Ôćĺpoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17Ôćĺ\n    18ÔćĺThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    19Ôćĺfile is a parse error.\n    20Ôćĺ\n    21Ôćĺ## Concepts\n    22Ôćĺ\n    23Ôćĺ| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    24Ôćĺ|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    25Ôćĺ| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    26Ôćĺ| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    27Ôćĺ| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    28Ôćĺ| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    29Ôćĺ| done     | Built-in terminal step ÔÇö successful completion                     |\n    30Ôćĺ| abort    | Built-in terminal step ÔÇö failure with error reporting              |\n    31Ôćĺ\n    32Ôćĺ## Step Types\n    33Ôćĺ\n    34ÔćĺStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    35Ôćĺ\n    36Ôćĺ**agent** (has `prompt`) ÔÇö Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    37Ôćĺto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    38Ôćĺcontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    39Ôćĺ\n    40Ôćĺ**script** (has `run`) ÔÇö Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    41Ôćĺany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    42Ôćĺ\n    43Ôćĺ**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) ÔÇö Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    44Ôćĺuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    45Ôćĺ\n    46ÔćĺA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    47Ôćĺparse error.\n    48Ôćĺ\n    49Ôćĺ## DSL Syntax\n    50Ôćĺ\n    51Ôćĺ```\n    52Ôćĺworkflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    53Ôćĺ  step code {\n    54Ôćĺ    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    55Ôćĺ    container {\n    56Ôćĺ      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    57Ôćĺ      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    58Ôćĺ    }\n    59Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    60Ôćĺ  }\n    61Ôćĺ\n    62Ôćĺ  step check {\n    63Ôćĺ    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    64Ôćĺ    results = [pass, fail]\n    65Ôćĺ  }\n    66Ôćĺ\n    67Ôćĺ  step review {\n    68Ôćĺ    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    69Ôćĺ    input = step.code.output\n    70Ôćĺ    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    71Ôćĺ  }\n    72Ôćĺ\n    73Ôćĺ  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n    74Ôćĺ  code:success -> check\n    75Ôćĺ  code:fail -> abort\n    76Ôćĺ  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n    77Ôćĺ\n    78Ôćĺ  check:pass -> review\n    79Ôćĺ  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n    80Ôćĺ\n    81Ôćĺ  review:approved -> done\n    82Ôćĺ  review:changes_requested -> code\n    83Ôćĺ}\n    84Ôćĺ```\n    85Ôćĺ\n    86Ôćĺ## Key Properties\n    87Ôćĺ\n    88Ôćĺ**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n    89Ôćĺfield makes it a script step.\n    90Ôćĺ\n    91Ôćĺ**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n    92Ôćĺreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n    93Ôćĺ\n    94Ôćĺ**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n    95Ôćĺexisting ones by rewiring ÔÇö without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n    96ÔćĺCloche's self-evolution feature.\n    97Ôćĺ\n    98Ôćĺ**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n    99Ôćĺwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   100Ôćĺ\n   101Ôćĺ## Wire Output Mappings\n   102Ôćĺ\n   103ÔćĺWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   104Ôćĺthem as environment variables into the target step:\n   105Ôćĺ\n   106Ôćĺ```\n   107Ôćĺstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   108Ôćĺ```\n   109Ôćĺ\n   110ÔćĺThe general form:\n   111Ôćĺ\n   112Ôćĺ```\n   113ÔćĺFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   114Ôćĺ```\n   115Ôćĺ\n   116ÔćĺWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   117Ôćĺstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   118Ôćĺ\n   119Ôćĺ| Expression | Meaning |\n   120Ôćĺ|---|---|\n   121Ôćĺ| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   122Ôćĺ| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   123Ôćĺ| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   124Ôćĺ| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   125Ôćĺ| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   126Ôćĺ\n   127ÔćĺIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   128Ôćĺstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   129Ôćĺvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   130Ôćĺ\n   131ÔćĺIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   132Ôćĺreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   133Ôćĺwires to different steps without conflict.\n   134Ôćĺ\n   135Ôćĺ## The `host {}` Block\n   136Ôćĺ\n   137ÔćĺHost workflows support a `host {}` block at the workflow level to configure agent\n   138Ôćĺdefaults for agent steps running on the host machine. Keys are stored with a `host.`\n   139Ôćĺprefix, analogous to the `container {}` block for container workflows.\n   140Ôćĺ\n   141Ôćĺ```\n   142Ôćĺworkflow \"main\" {\n   143Ôćĺ  host {\n   144Ôćĺ    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   145Ôćĺ  }\n   146Ôćĺ  ...\n   147Ôćĺ}\n   148Ôćĺ```\n   149Ôćĺ\n   150ÔćĺSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   151Ôćĺ`agent_args` override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults. The agent command\n   152Ôćĺresolution order for host agent steps is the same as for container agent steps:\n   153Ôćĺstep-level > workflow-level `host {}` > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var > default\n   154Ôćĺ`claude`.\n   155Ôćĺ\n   156Ôćĺ## Host Workflow Example\n   157Ôćĺ\n   158Ôćĺ```\n   159Ôćĺ# .cloche/host.cloche ÔÇö runs on the host machine\n   160Ôćĺworkflow \"main\" {\n   161Ôćĺ  host {\n   162Ôćĺ    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   163Ôćĺ  }\n   164Ôćĺ\n   165Ôćĺ  step ready-tasks {\n   166Ôćĺ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh 1\"\n   167Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail]\n   168Ôćĺ  }\n   169Ôćĺ\n   170Ôćĺ  step prepare-prompt {\n   171Ôćĺ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   172Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail]\n   173Ôćĺ  }\n   174Ôćĺ\n   175Ôćĺ  step develop {\n   176Ôćĺ    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   177Ôćĺ    results       = [success, fail]\n   178Ôćĺ  }\n   179Ôćĺ\n   180Ôćĺ  ready-tasks:success -> prepare-prompt [\n   181Ôćĺ    CLOCHE_TASK_ID    = output[0].id,\n   182Ôćĺ    CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE = output[0].title,\n   183Ôćĺ    CLOCHE_TASK_BODY  = output[0].description\n   184Ôćĺ  ]\n   185Ôćĺ  ready-tasks:fail       -> abort\n   186Ôćĺ  prepare-prompt:success -> develop [\n   187Ôćĺ    CLOCHE_TASK_ID = output.task_id\n   188Ôćĺ  ]\n   189Ôćĺ  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   190Ôćĺ  develop:success        -> done\n   191Ôćĺ  develop:fail           -> done\n   192Ôćĺ}\n   193Ôćĺ```\n   194Ôćĺ\n   195ÔćĺThe `ready-tasks` step outputs JSON; wire output mappings extract fields and inject\n   196Ôćĺthem as environment variables into `prepare-prompt`. The `workflow_name` step\n   197Ôćĺdispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes.\n   198Ôćĺ\n   199Ôćĺ## Execution Model\n   200Ôćĺ\n   201Ôćĺ**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   202Ôćĺcontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   203Ôćĺwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   204ÔćĺAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   205Ôćĺ\n   206Ôćĺ**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\n   207Ôćĺsteps run via `sh -c` with the working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e.\n   208Ôćĺthe main branch checkout), even if the project directory is a linked worktree on a\n   209Ôćĺdifferent branch. This ensures host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs.\n   210ÔćĺWorkflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline.\n   211ÔćĺEnvironment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into\n   212Ôćĺeach step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still points to the actual project directory.\n   213Ôćĺ"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Dpfoc28ynQqDwHgSbSci6o","session_id":"2f8bcbbf-b8aa-4f20-9779-dee3a5fa668b","uuid":"697b3dbf-5b53-4af4-b33e-9eb821e353eb"}
