[2026-03-11T00:27:32Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Q4Lp62K5jAzMpJcHTEsRUH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `TestLoop_TaskAssigner_DedupExpires` test failed. The issue is that the dedup window expires after 50ms, but the loop goes through the idle poll interval (30s) after the first run because the run finishes, then the loop needs to pick up again. Let me look at the loop logic more carefully.\n\nAfter a successful run, the loop immediately tries to fill slots again (the `continue` on success). But the issue is: after task-1 is assigned and the run completes (succeeds in ~10ms), the loop tries to pick another task. At that point (~10-20ms), the dedup hasn't expired yet (50ms), so pickTask returns false, the inner `for` breaks, and now `inFlight == 0`. It then sleeps for `capacityPollInterval` (5s), which is way too long for our 50ms dedup window.\n \nTracing through the execution: task-1 gets picked and launched, then the inner loop exits because we've hit max concurrency. The run completes quickly, and on the next iteration pickTask fails since the dedup window hasn't elapsed yet, causing the inner loop to break with no in-flight tasks. This triggers the long sleep interval instead of retrying sooner.\n\nThe core issue is that the 5-second capacity poll interval is way too long compared to the 50-millisecond dedup timeout and the test's 300-millisecond timeout. I need to either shorten the poll interval, extend the test sleep, or adjust the dedup timeout to make the test pass. I think the cleanest solution is to adjust the dedup timeout to around 100ms and give the test enough time to let that expire and pick up the task again, rather than fighting against the 5-second capacity poll interval.\n\nActually, the real problem is that 5-second waitÔÇöwhen there are no tasks available and a task assigner is configured, we should be polling much more frequently instead of blocking for that long. Let me introduce a shorter `taskPollInterval` that kicks in when we're waiting for tasks to become available.\n\nOr simpler: I could adjust the test itself so the run duration exceeds the dedup window, which means by the time the first run finishes, the dedup timeout has already expired and we can pick the task again without waiting.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2918,"cache_read_input_tokens":96952,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2918},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2f8bcbbf-b8aa-4f20-9779-dee3a5fa668b","uuid":"c0273d44-4da4-4908-b189-1922e5f42caf"}
