[2026-03-11T00:29:45Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011w2DxmdQem41CYrQBhKPZZ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1Ôćĺ# Host Workflow Design (`host.cloche`)\n     2Ôćĺ\n     3Ôćĺ**Date:** 2026-03-06\n     4Ôćĺ**Status:** Design\n     5Ôćĺ\n     6Ôćĺ## Problem\n     7Ôćĺ\n     8ÔćĺThe orchestrator's intake Ôćĺ process Ôćĺ output loop is hard-coded in Go\n     9Ôćĺ(`internal/orchestrator/orchestrator.go`). Every project must follow the same flow:\n    10Ôćĺpull task Ôćĺ generate prompt Ôćĺ dispatch `develop` container run. This can't be changed\n    11Ôćĺwithout modifying Cloche itself. Projects that need different orchestration strategies\n    12Ôćĺ(push to GitHub for review, group tickets into feature branches, stacked commits, etc.)\n    13Ôćĺhave no extension point.\n    14Ôćĺ\n    15Ôćĺ## Solution: `host.cloche`\n    16Ôćĺ\n    17ÔćĺA special workflow file at `.cloche/host.cloche`. It uses the same DSL as container\n    18Ôćĺworkflow files, with one additional step type (`workflow`). Steps in this file execute\n    19Ôćĺon the **host machine**, not inside a container.\n    20Ôćĺ\n    21ÔćĺThe workflow named `main` in this file becomes the per-task orchestration loop\n    22Ôćĺfor that project. The Go daemon becomes the executor of this workflow rather than the\n    23Ôćĺhard-coded logic holder.\n    24Ôćĺ\n    25Ôćĺ### File location\n    26Ôćĺ\n    27Ôćĺ```\n    28Ôćĺ.cloche/host.cloche\n    29Ôćĺ```\n    30Ôćĺ\n    31ÔćĺIf the file does not exist, the daemon falls back to the current hard-coded behavior\n    32Ôćĺ(pull task Ôćĺ LLM prompt generation Ôćĺ dispatch container workflow).\n    33Ôćĺ\n    34Ôćĺ---\n    35Ôćĺ\n    36Ôćĺ## DSL additions\n    37Ôćĺ\n    38Ôćĺ### New step type: `workflow`\n    39Ôćĺ\n    40ÔćĺA step with `workflow_name` config key is a workflow-dispatch step. It dispatches a\n    41Ôćĺnamed container workflow run and blocks until that run completes.\n    42Ôćĺ\n    43Ôćĺ```\n    44Ôćĺstep develop {\n    45Ôćĺ  workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    46Ôćĺ  results = [success, fail]\n    47Ôćĺ}\n    48Ôćĺ```\n    49Ôćĺ\n    50Ôćĺ`workflow_name` is added to `knownStepConfigKeys` in `domain/workflow.go`.\n    51Ôćĺ\n    52Ôćĺ`StepTypeWorkflow` is added to the `StepType` enum in `domain/workflow.go`.\n    53Ôćĺ\n    54ÔćĺThe parser (`dsl/parser.go`) infers `StepTypeWorkflow` when `workflow_name` is present\n    55Ôćĺ(same pattern as `run` Ôćĺ script, `prompt` Ôćĺ agent).\n    56Ôćĺ\n    57Ôćĺ### Prompt input for `workflow` steps\n    58Ôćĺ\n    59ÔćĺThe container workflow needs a prompt. By convention, a `workflow` step reads the\n    60Ôćĺprevious step's captured output file as the prompt. This is the primary data-passing\n    61Ôćĺmechanism.\n    62Ôćĺ\n    63ÔćĺAn optional config key `prompt_step` overrides which step's output to read:\n    64Ôćĺ```\n    65Ôćĺstep develop {\n    66Ôćĺ  workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    67Ôćĺ  prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n    68Ôćĺ  results       = [success, fail]\n    69Ôćĺ}\n    70Ôćĺ```\n    71Ôćĺ\n    72Ôćĺ---\n    73Ôćĺ\n    74Ôćĺ## Step output capture\n    75Ôćĺ\n    76ÔćĺEvery step in a host workflow execution writes its output (stdout of `run` steps,\n    77Ôćĺfinal response of `prompt` steps) to a file:\n    78Ôćĺ\n    79Ôćĺ```\n    80Ôćĺ.cloche/<orch-run-id>/main/<step_name>.out\n    81Ôćĺ```\n    82Ôćĺ\n    83Ôćĺ`<orch-run-id>` is a unique ID for this orchestration invocation, formatted the same\n    84Ôćĺway as workflow run IDs (e.g. `main-bold-hawk`).\n    85Ôćĺ\n    86ÔćĺThe daemon tracks the most recently completed step's output path and passes it to the\n    87Ôćĺnext step as `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT`.\n    88Ôćĺ\n    89Ôćĺ---\n    90Ôćĺ\n    91Ôćĺ## Environment variables injected into host steps\n    92Ôćĺ\n    93ÔćĺAll `run` and `prompt` steps receive:\n    94Ôćĺ\n    95Ôćĺ| Variable | Value |\n    96Ôćĺ|----------|-------|\n    97Ôćĺ| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID being processed |\n    98Ôćĺ| `CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE` | Task summary/title |\n    99Ôćĺ| `CLOCHE_TASK_BODY` | Task full body/description |\n   100Ôćĺ| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory |\n   101Ôćĺ| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output |\n   102Ôćĺ| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the previous step's output file |\n   103Ôćĺ\n   104ÔćĺFor `workflow` steps, `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` is read automatically (unless `prompt_step`\n   105Ôćĺoverrides it).\n   106Ôćĺ\n   107Ôćĺ---\n   108Ôćĺ\n   109Ôćĺ## Executor: `internal/orchestrator/hostrunner.go`\n   110Ôćĺ\n   111ÔćĺNew file. Implements the host workflow execution loop.\n   112Ôćĺ\n   113Ôćĺ```go\n   114Ôćĺtype HostRunner struct {\n   115Ôćĺ    Dispatch  RunDispatcher      // existing: dispatches a container workflow run\n   116Ôćĺ    WaitRun   RunWaiter          // new: blocks until a run ID completes, returns final state\n   117Ôćĺ    AgentCmd  string             // command to invoke for prompt steps on host\n   118Ôćĺ}\n   119Ôćĺ\n   120Ôćĺ// RunWorkflow executes the named workflow from a parsed host.cloche Workflow\n   121Ôćĺ// for a single task. Returns the final result (\"done\" or \"abort\").\n   122Ôćĺfunc (r *HostRunner) RunWorkflow(ctx context.Context, wf *domain.Workflow, task ports.Task, orchRunID string) (string, error)\n   123Ôćĺ```\n   124Ôćĺ\n   125ÔćĺStep execution:\n   126Ôćĺ\n   127Ôćĺ- **`script` step** (`run` key): `exec.Command` with env vars, stdout captured to\n   128Ôćĺ  `<step>.out`, stderr to `<step>.err`. Exit 0 Ôćĺ `success`, non-zero Ôćĺ `fail`.\n   129Ôćĺ- **`agent` step** (`prompt` key): invoke `AgentCmd` on host with the prompt file\n   130Ôćĺ  contents injected. Capture output. Exit 0 Ôćĺ `success`, non-zero Ôćĺ `fail`.\n   131Ôćĺ- **`workflow` step** (`workflow_name` key): read prompt from prev step's `.out` file\n   132Ôćĺ  (or `prompt_step` override), call `Dispatch`, then call `WaitRun` to block until\n   133Ôćĺ  the container run completes. Map `succeeded` Ôćĺ `success`, `failed`/`cancelled` Ôćĺ\n   134Ôćĺ  `fail`.\n   135Ôćĺ\n   136Ôćĺ`WaitRun` is a new port interface:\n   137Ôćĺ\n   138Ôćĺ```go\n   139Ôćĺ// RunWaiter blocks until the run with the given ID reaches a terminal state.\n   140Ôćĺtype RunWaiter interface {\n   141Ôćĺ    WaitRun(ctx context.Context, runID string) (domain.RunState, error)\n   142Ôćĺ}\n   143Ôćĺ```\n   144Ôćĺ\n   145ÔćĺThe gRPC server / store already has `GetRun`; the waiter can poll it with backoff or\n   146Ôćĺsubscribe to the `OnRunComplete` event. A simple polling implementation (1s interval)\n   147Ôćĺis sufficient initially.\n   148Ôćĺ\n   149Ôćĺ---\n   150Ôćĺ\n   151Ôćĺ## Refactored `orchestrator.Orchestrator`\n   152Ôćĺ\n   153Ôćĺ`Orchestrator.Run()` is updated:\n   154Ôćĺ\n   155Ôćĺ**Current flow (hardcoded):**\n   156Ôćĺ1. Pull ready tasks\n   157Ôćĺ2. Claim task\n   158Ôćĺ3. Call `promptGen.Generate(task)`\n   159Ôćĺ4. Call `dispatch(workflow, projectDir, prompt)` Ôćĺ runID\n   160Ôćĺ5. (In-flight counter managed, `OnRunComplete` decrements it)\n   161Ôćĺ\n   162Ôćĺ**New flow (when `host.cloche` exists):**\n   163Ôćĺ1. Pull ready tasks\n   164Ôćĺ2. Claim task\n   165Ôćĺ3. Parse `.cloche/host.cloche` Ôćĺ find `main` workflow\n   166Ôćĺ4. Generate an `orchRunID` (`main-<namegen>`)\n   167Ôćĺ5. Spin up a goroutine: call `hostRunner.RunWorkflow(ctx, orch wf, task, orchRunID)`\n   168Ôćĺ6. On goroutine return: decrement in-flight, update task state (success/fail)\n   169Ôćĺ\n   170ÔćĺThe old `promptGen` and `dispatch` are still used as the **fallback** when\n   171Ôćĺ`host.cloche` is absent (no breaking change for existing projects).\n   172Ôćĺ\n   173Ôćĺ`WaitRun` needs access to the run store. Wire it in `initOrchestrator` in\n   174Ôćĺ`cmd/cloched/main.go`.\n   175Ôćĺ\n   176Ôćĺ---\n   177Ôćĺ\n   178Ôćĺ## Default `host.cloche` (from `cloche init`)\n   179Ôćĺ\n   180Ôćĺ```\n   181Ôćĺ# host.cloche ÔÇö orchestration workflow (runs on host, not in container)\n   182Ôćĺ# Steps here execute as the daemon user. Keep operations simple and safe.\n   183Ôćĺ\n   184Ôćĺworkflow \"main\" {\n   185Ôćĺ  step prepare-prompt {\n   186Ôćĺ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   187Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail]\n   188Ôćĺ  }\n   189Ôćĺ\n   190Ôćĺ  step develop {\n   191Ôćĺ    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   192Ôćĺ    results       = [success, fail]\n   193Ôćĺ  }\n   194Ôćĺ\n   195Ôćĺ  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   196Ôćĺ  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   197Ôćĺ  develop:success        -> done\n   198Ôćĺ  develop:fail           -> done\n   199Ôćĺ}\n   200Ôćĺ```\n   201Ôćĺ\n   202ÔćĺAnd `.cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` (created by init, chmod +x):\n   203Ôćĺ\n   204Ôćĺ```bash\n   205Ôćĺ#!/usr/bin/env bash\n   206Ôćĺ# Default prompt generator. Uses task env vars injected by cloched.\n   207Ôćĺ# Write the prompt to $CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT (also echoed to stdout).\n   208Ôćĺset -euo pipefail\n   209Ôćĺ\n   210Ôćĺprompt=\"## Task: ${CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE}\n   211Ôćĺ\n   212Ôćĺ${CLOCHE_TASK_BODY}\"\n   213Ôćĺ\n   214Ôćĺecho \"$prompt\"\n   215Ôćĺ[ -n \"${CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT:-}\" ] && echo \"$prompt\" > \"$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT\"\n   216Ôćĺ```\n   217Ôćĺ\n   218Ôćĺ---\n   219Ôćĺ\n   220Ôćĺ## `.gitignore` update\n   221Ôćĺ\n   222Ôćĺ`cloche init` adds `.cloche/scripts/` is NOT gitignored (scripts are project config).\n   223ÔćĺThe orchestration run output dirs follow the same pattern as container run dirs:\n   224Ôćĺ`.cloche/main-*/` is gitignored via the existing `.cloche/*/` rule.\n   225Ôćĺ\n   226Ôćĺ---\n   227Ôćĺ\n   228Ôćĺ## Safety notes\n   229Ôćĺ\n   230Ôćĺ- Host steps run with the same OS privileges as the `cloched` process.\n   231Ôćĺ- No network isolation.\n   232Ôćĺ- `host.cloche` should only reference scripts that are committed to the project.\n   233Ôćĺ- Document that `prompt` steps in `host.cloche` invoke an LLM agent with full host\n   234Ôćĺ  filesystem access ÔÇö use judiciously.\n   235Ôćĺ\n   236Ôćĺ---\n   237Ôćĺ\n   238Ôćĺ## Changes required\n   239Ôćĺ\n   240Ôćĺ| File | Change |\n   241Ôćĺ|------|--------|\n   242Ôćĺ| `internal/domain/workflow.go` | Add `StepTypeWorkflow`, add `workflow_name`/`prompt_step` to `knownStepConfigKeys` |\n   243Ôćĺ| `internal/dsl/parser.go` | Infer `StepTypeWorkflow` when `workflow_name` key is present |\n   244Ôćĺ| `internal/orchestrator/hostrunner.go` | New: host workflow executor |\n   245Ôćĺ| `internal/orchestrator/orchestrator.go` | Refactor `Run()` to use `HostRunner` when `host.cloche` exists; fall back to current behavior otherwise |\n   246Ôćĺ| `internal/ports/container.go` | Add `RunWaiter` interface |\n   247Ôćĺ| `cmd/cloched/main.go` | Wire `HostRunner` into orchestrator init |\n   248Ôćĺ| `cmd/cloche/init.go` | Create `host.cloche` and `scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` |\n   249Ôćĺ"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b83aa53c-b539-403e-957d-d27f065bd09c","uuid":"2a4629b0-d9e6-4b38-ad1b-eac4b9bffa61","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-03-06-host-workflow-design.md","content":"# Host Workflow Design (`host.cloche`)\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-06\n**Status:** Design\n\n## Problem\n\nThe orchestrator's intake Ôćĺ process Ôćĺ output loop is hard-coded in Go\n(`internal/orchestrator/orchestrator.go`). Every project must follow the same flow:\npull task Ôćĺ generate prompt Ôćĺ dispatch `develop` container run. This can't be changed\nwithout modifying Cloche itself. Projects that need different orchestration strategies\n(push to GitHub for review, group tickets into feature branches, stacked commits, etc.)\nhave no extension point.\n\n## Solution: `host.cloche`\n\nA special workflow file at `.cloche/host.cloche`. It uses the same DSL as container\nworkflow files, with one additional step type (`workflow`). Steps in this file execute\non the **host machine**, not inside a container.\n\nThe workflow named `main` in this file becomes the per-task orchestration loop\nfor that project. The Go daemon becomes the executor of this workflow rather than the\nhard-coded logic holder.\n\n### File location\n\n```\n.cloche/host.cloche\n```\n\nIf the file does not exist, the daemon falls back to the current hard-coded behavior\n(pull task Ôćĺ LLM prompt generation Ôćĺ dispatch container workflow).\n\n---\n\n## DSL additions\n\n### New step type: `workflow`\n\nA step with `workflow_name` config key is a workflow-dispatch step. It dispatches a\nnamed container workflow run and blocks until that run completes.\n\n```\nstep develop {\n  workflow_name = \"develop\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n`workflow_name` is added to `knownStepConfigKeys` in `domain/workflow.go`.\n\n`StepTypeWorkflow` is added to the `StepType` enum in `domain/workflow.go`.\n\nThe parser (`dsl/parser.go`) infers `StepTypeWorkflow` when `workflow_name` is present\n(same pattern as `run` Ôćĺ script, `prompt` Ôćĺ agent).\n\n### Prompt input for `workflow` steps\n\nThe container workflow needs a prompt. By convention, a `workflow` step reads the\nprevious step's captured output file as the prompt. This is the primary data-passing\nmechanism.\n\nAn optional config key `prompt_step` overrides which step's output to read:\n```\nstep develop {\n  workflow_name = \"develop\"\n  prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n  results       = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step output capture\n\nEvery step in a host workflow execution writes its output (stdout of `run` steps,\nfinal response of `prompt` steps) to a file:\n\n```\n.cloche/<orch-run-id>/main/<step_name>.out\n```\n\n`<orch-run-id>` is a unique ID for this orchestration invocation, formatted the same\nway as workflow run IDs (e.g. `main-bold-hawk`).\n\nThe daemon tracks the most recently completed step's output path and passes it to the\nnext step as `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT`.\n\n---\n\n## Environment variables injected into host steps\n\nAll `run` and `prompt` steps receive:\n\n| Variable | Value |\n|----------|-------|\n| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID being processed |\n| `CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE` | Task summary/title |\n| `CLOCHE_TASK_BODY` | Task full body/description |\n| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory |\n| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output |\n| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the previous step's output file |\n\nFor `workflow` steps, `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` is read automatically (unless `prompt_step`\noverrides it).\n\n---\n\n## Executor: `internal/orchestrator/hostrunner.go`\n\nNew file. Implements the host workflow execution loop.\n\n```go\ntype HostRunner struct {\n    Dispatch  RunDispatcher      // existing: dispatches a container workflow run\n    WaitRun   RunWaiter          // new: blocks until a run ID completes, returns final state\n    AgentCmd  string             // command to invoke for prompt steps on host\n}\n\n// RunWorkflow executes the named workflow from a parsed host.cloche Workflow\n// for a single task. Returns the final result (\"done\" or \"abort\").\nfunc (r *HostRunner) RunWorkflow(ctx context.Context, wf *domain.Workflow, task ports.Task, orchRunID string) (string, error)\n```\n\nStep execution:\n\n- **`script` step** (`run` key): `exec.Command` with env vars, stdout captured to\n  `<step>.out`, stderr to `<step>.err`. Exit 0 Ôćĺ `success`, non-zero Ôćĺ `fail`.\n- **`agent` step** (`prompt` key): invoke `AgentCmd` on host with the prompt file\n  contents injected. Capture output. Exit 0 Ôćĺ `success`, non-zero Ôćĺ `fail`.\n- **`workflow` step** (`workflow_name` key): read prompt from prev step's `.out` file\n  (or `prompt_step` override), call `Dispatch`, then call `WaitRun` to block until\n  the container run completes. Map `succeeded` Ôćĺ `success`, `failed`/`cancelled` Ôćĺ\n  `fail`.\n\n`WaitRun` is a new port interface:\n\n```go\n// RunWaiter blocks until the run with the given ID reaches a terminal state.\ntype RunWaiter interface {\n    WaitRun(ctx context.Context, runID string) (domain.RunState, error)\n}\n```\n\nThe gRPC server / store already has `GetRun`; the waiter can poll it with backoff or\nsubscribe to the `OnRunComplete` event. A simple polling implementation (1s interval)\nis sufficient initially.\n\n---\n\n## Refactored `orchestrator.Orchestrator`\n\n`Orchestrator.Run()` is updated:\n\n**Current flow (hardcoded):**\n1. Pull ready tasks\n2. Claim task\n3. Call `promptGen.Generate(task)`\n4. Call `dispatch(workflow, projectDir, prompt)` Ôćĺ runID\n5. (In-flight counter managed, `OnRunComplete` decrements it)\n\n**New flow (when `host.cloche` exists):**\n1. Pull ready tasks\n2. Claim task\n3. Parse `.cloche/host.cloche` Ôćĺ find `main` workflow\n4. Generate an `orchRunID` (`main-<namegen>`)\n5. Spin up a goroutine: call `hostRunner.RunWorkflow(ctx, orch wf, task, orchRunID)`\n6. On goroutine return: decrement in-flight, update task state (success/fail)\n\nThe old `promptGen` and `dispatch` are still used as the **fallback** when\n`host.cloche` is absent (no breaking change for existing projects).\n\n`WaitRun` needs access to the run store. Wire it in `initOrchestrator` in\n`cmd/cloched/main.go`.\n\n---\n\n## Default `host.cloche` (from `cloche init`)\n\n```\n# host.cloche ÔÇö orchestration workflow (runs on host, not in container)\n# Steps here execute as the daemon user. Keep operations simple and safe.\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n```\n\nAnd `.cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` (created by init, chmod +x):\n\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Default prompt generator. Uses task env vars injected by cloched.\n# Write the prompt to $CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT (also echoed to stdout).\nset -euo pipefail\n\nprompt=\"## Task: ${CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE}\n\n${CLOCHE_TASK_BODY}\"\n\necho \"$prompt\"\n[ -n \"${CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT:-}\" ] && echo \"$prompt\" > \"$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## `.gitignore` update\n\n`cloche init` adds `.cloche/scripts/` is NOT gitignored (scripts are project config).\nThe orchestration run output dirs follow the same pattern as container run dirs:\n`.cloche/main-*/` is gitignored via the existing `.cloche/*/` rule.\n\n---\n\n## Safety notes\n\n- Host steps run with the same OS privileges as the `cloched` process.\n- No network isolation.\n- `host.cloche` should only reference scripts that are committed to the project.\n- Document that `prompt` steps in `host.cloche` invoke an LLM agent with full host\n  filesystem access ÔÇö use judiciously.\n\n---\n\n## Changes required\n\n| File | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| `internal/domain/workflow.go` | Add `StepTypeWorkflow`, add `workflow_name`/`prompt_step` to `knownStepConfigKeys` |\n| `internal/dsl/parser.go` | Infer `StepTypeWorkflow` when `workflow_name` key is present |\n| `internal/orchestrator/hostrunner.go` | New: host workflow executor |\n| `internal/orchestrator/orchestrator.go` | Refactor `Run()` to use `HostRunner` when `host.cloche` exists; fall back to current behavior otherwise |\n| `internal/ports/container.go` | Add `RunWaiter` interface |\n| `cmd/cloched/main.go` | Wire `HostRunner` into orchestrator init |\n| `cmd/cloche/init.go` | Create `host.cloche` and `scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` |\n","numLines":249,"startLine":1,"totalLines":249}}}
[2026-03-11T00:29:45Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01SioY7VTvuLH4SsxGJCEZzo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01HaCdgTB6N9GHjb4peWmMpo","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4656,"cache_read_input_tokens":14566,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4656},"output_tokens":12,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b83aa53c-b539-403e-957d-d27f065bd09c","uuid":"7b3f28f5-0171-490a-a262-a4df875614d3"}
[2026-03-11T00:29:45Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HaCdgTB6N9GHjb4peWmMpo","type":"tool_result","content":"     1Ôćĺ# Workflows\n     2Ôćĺ\n     3ÔćĺCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4Ôćĺ\n     5Ôćĺ## Workflow Locations\n     6Ôćĺ\n     7ÔćĺCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8Ôćĺ\n     9Ôćĺ**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) ÔÇö Run inside a Docker\n    10Ôćĺcontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11Ôćĺstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12Ôćĺ\n    13Ôćĺ**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) ÔÇö Runs on the host machine as the daemon\n    14Ôćĺprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15Ôćĺdispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16Ôćĺpoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17Ôćĺ\n    18ÔćĺThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    19Ôćĺfile is a parse error.\n    20Ôćĺ\n    21Ôćĺ## Concepts\n    22Ôćĺ\n    23Ôćĺ| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    24Ôćĺ|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    25Ôćĺ| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    26Ôćĺ| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    27Ôćĺ| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    28Ôćĺ| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    29Ôćĺ| done     | Built-in terminal step ÔÇö successful completion                     |\n    30Ôćĺ| abort    | Built-in terminal step ÔÇö failure with error reporting              |\n    31Ôćĺ\n    32Ôćĺ## Step Types\n    33Ôćĺ\n    34ÔćĺStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    35Ôćĺ\n    36Ôćĺ**agent** (has `prompt`) ÔÇö Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    37Ôćĺto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    38Ôćĺcontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    39Ôćĺ\n    40Ôćĺ**script** (has `run`) ÔÇö Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    41Ôćĺany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    42Ôćĺ\n    43Ôćĺ**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) ÔÇö Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    44Ôćĺuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    45Ôćĺ\n    46ÔćĺA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    47Ôćĺparse error.\n    48Ôćĺ\n    49Ôćĺ## DSL Syntax\n    50Ôćĺ\n    51Ôćĺ```\n    52Ôćĺworkflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    53Ôćĺ  step code {\n    54Ôćĺ    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    55Ôćĺ    container {\n    56Ôćĺ      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    57Ôćĺ      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    58Ôćĺ    }\n    59Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    60Ôćĺ  }\n    61Ôćĺ\n    62Ôćĺ  step check {\n    63Ôćĺ    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    64Ôćĺ    results = [pass, fail]\n    65Ôćĺ  }\n    66Ôćĺ\n    67Ôćĺ  step review {\n    68Ôćĺ    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    69Ôćĺ    input = step.code.output\n    70Ôćĺ    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    71Ôćĺ  }\n    72Ôćĺ\n    73Ôćĺ  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n    74Ôćĺ  code:success -> check\n    75Ôćĺ  code:fail -> abort\n    76Ôćĺ  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n    77Ôćĺ\n    78Ôćĺ  check:pass -> review\n    79Ôćĺ  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n    80Ôćĺ\n    81Ôćĺ  review:approved -> done\n    82Ôćĺ  review:changes_requested -> code\n    83Ôćĺ}\n    84Ôćĺ```\n    85Ôćĺ\n    86Ôćĺ## Key Properties\n    87Ôćĺ\n    88Ôćĺ**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n    89Ôćĺfield makes it a script step.\n    90Ôćĺ\n    91Ôćĺ**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n    92Ôćĺreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n    93Ôćĺ\n    94Ôćĺ**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n    95Ôćĺexisting ones by rewiring ÔÇö without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n    96ÔćĺCloche's self-evolution feature.\n    97Ôćĺ\n    98Ôćĺ**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n    99Ôćĺwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   100Ôćĺ\n   101Ôćĺ## Wire Output Mappings\n   102Ôćĺ\n   103ÔćĺWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   104Ôćĺthem as environment variables into the target step:\n   105Ôćĺ\n   106Ôćĺ```\n   107Ôćĺstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   108Ôćĺ```\n   109Ôćĺ\n   110ÔćĺThe general form:\n   111Ôćĺ\n   112Ôćĺ```\n   113ÔćĺFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   114Ôćĺ```\n   115Ôćĺ\n   116ÔćĺWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   117Ôćĺstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   118Ôćĺ\n   119Ôćĺ| Expression | Meaning |\n   120Ôćĺ|---|---|\n   121Ôćĺ| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   122Ôćĺ| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   123Ôćĺ| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   124Ôćĺ| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   125Ôćĺ| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   126Ôćĺ\n   127ÔćĺIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   128Ôćĺstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   129Ôćĺvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   130Ôćĺ\n   131ÔćĺIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   132Ôćĺreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   133Ôćĺwires to different steps without conflict.\n   134Ôćĺ\n   135Ôćĺ## The `host {}` Block\n   136Ôćĺ\n   137ÔćĺHost workflows support a `host {}` block at the workflow level to configure agent\n   138Ôćĺdefaults for agent steps running on the host machine. Keys are stored with a `host.`\n   139Ôćĺprefix, analogous to the `container {}` block for container workflows.\n   140Ôćĺ\n   141Ôćĺ```\n   142Ôćĺworkflow \"main\" {\n   143Ôćĺ  host {\n   144Ôćĺ    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   145Ôćĺ  }\n   146Ôćĺ  ...\n   147Ôćĺ}\n   148Ôćĺ```\n   149Ôćĺ\n   150ÔćĺSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   151Ôćĺ`agent_args` override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults. The agent command\n   152Ôćĺresolution order for host agent steps is the same as for container agent steps:\n   153Ôćĺstep-level > workflow-level `host {}` > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var > default\n   154Ôćĺ`claude`.\n   155Ôćĺ\n   156Ôćĺ## Host Workflow Example\n   157Ôćĺ\n   158Ôćĺ```\n   159Ôćĺ# .cloche/host.cloche ÔÇö runs on the host machine\n   160Ôćĺworkflow \"main\" {\n   161Ôćĺ  host {\n   162Ôćĺ    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   163Ôćĺ  }\n   164Ôćĺ\n   165Ôćĺ  step ready-tasks {\n   166Ôćĺ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh 1\"\n   167Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail]\n   168Ôćĺ  }\n   169Ôćĺ\n   170Ôćĺ  step prepare-prompt {\n   171Ôćĺ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   172Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail]\n   173Ôćĺ  }\n   174Ôćĺ\n   175Ôćĺ  step develop {\n   176Ôćĺ    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   177Ôćĺ    results       = [success, fail]\n   178Ôćĺ  }\n   179Ôćĺ\n   180Ôćĺ  ready-tasks:success -> prepare-prompt [\n   181Ôćĺ    CLOCHE_TASK_ID    = output[0].id,\n   182Ôćĺ    CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE = output[0].title,\n   183Ôćĺ    CLOCHE_TASK_BODY  = output[0].description\n   184Ôćĺ  ]\n   185Ôćĺ  ready-tasks:fail       -> abort\n   186Ôćĺ  prepare-prompt:success -> develop [\n   187Ôćĺ    CLOCHE_TASK_ID = output.task_id\n   188Ôćĺ  ]\n   189Ôćĺ  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   190Ôćĺ  develop:success        -> done\n   191Ôćĺ  develop:fail           -> done\n   192Ôćĺ}\n   193Ôćĺ```\n   194Ôćĺ\n   195ÔćĺThe `ready-tasks` step outputs JSON; wire output mappings extract fields and inject\n   196Ôćĺthem as environment variables into `prepare-prompt`. The `workflow_name` step\n   197Ôćĺdispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes.\n   198Ôćĺ\n   199Ôćĺ## Execution Model\n   200Ôćĺ\n   201Ôćĺ**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   202Ôćĺcontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   203Ôćĺwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   204ÔćĺAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   205Ôćĺ\n   206Ôćĺ**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\n   207Ôćĺsteps run via `sh -c` with the working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e.\n   208Ôćĺthe main branch checkout), even if the project directory is a linked worktree on a\n   209Ôćĺdifferent branch. This ensures host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs.\n   210ÔćĺWorkflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline.\n   211ÔćĺEnvironment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into\n   212Ôćĺeach step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still points to the actual project directory.\n   213Ôćĺ"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b83aa53c-b539-403e-957d-d27f065bd09c","uuid":"c56d044e-3345-4326-a412-03379fad9fe4","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) ÔÇö Run inside a Docker\ncontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\nstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n\n**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) ÔÇö Runs on the host machine as the daemon\nprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\npoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step ÔÇö successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step ÔÇö failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) ÔÇö Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) ÔÇö Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) ÔÇö Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"implement-feature\" {\n  step code {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    container {\n      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    }\n    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n  }\n\n  step check {\n    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    results = [pass, fail]\n  }\n\n  step review {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    input = step.code.output\n    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n  }\n\n  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n  code:success -> check\n  code:fail -> abort\n  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n\n  check:pass -> review\n  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n\n  review:approved -> done\n  review:changes_requested -> code\n}\n```\n\n## Key Properties\n\n**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\nfield makes it a script step.\n\n**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\nreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n\n**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\nexisting ones by rewiring ÔÇö without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\nCloche's self-evolution feature.\n\n**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\nwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n\n## Wire Output Mappings\n\nWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\nthem as environment variables into the target step:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nThe general form:\n\n```\nFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n```\n\nWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\nstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\nstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\nvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n\nIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\nreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\nwires to different steps without conflict.\n\n## The `host {}` Block\n\nHost workflows support a `host {}` block at the workflow level to configure agent\ndefaults for agent steps running on the host machine. Keys are stored with a `host.`\nprefix, analogous to the `container {}` block for container workflows.\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n`agent_args` override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults. The agent command\nresolution order for host agent steps is the same as for container agent steps:\nstep-level > workflow-level `host {}` > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var > default\n`claude`.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\n```\n# .cloche/host.cloche ÔÇö runs on the host machine\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step ready-tasks {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh 1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  ready-tasks:success -> prepare-prompt [\n    CLOCHE_TASK_ID    = output[0].id,\n    CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE = output[0].title,\n    CLOCHE_TASK_BODY  = output[0].description\n  ]\n  ready-tasks:fail       -> abort\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop [\n    CLOCHE_TASK_ID = output.task_id\n  ]\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `ready-tasks` step outputs JSON; wire output mappings extract fields and inject\nthem as environment variables into `prepare-prompt`. The `workflow_name` step\ndispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes.\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\nsteps run via `sh -c` with the working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e.\nthe main branch checkout), even if the project directory is a linked worktree on a\ndifferent branch. This ensures host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs.\nWorkflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline.\nEnvironment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into\neach step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still points to the actual project directory.\n","numLines":213,"startLine":1,"totalLines":213}}}
